                            jump to other results
                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" htag="li" hclass="sense" id="auden_sng_1"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">Wystan Hugh Auden (1907-73) an English poet who wrote poems of many different types, often using traditional forms of <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/verse#verse_sng_1" title="verse definition"><span class="ndv">verse</span></a> but with modern language. He also wrote the words for <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/opera#opera_sng_1" title="operas definition"><span class="ndv">operas</span></a> and a famous <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/publicity" title="publicity definition"><span class="ndv">publicity</span></a> film for the <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/post-office" title="Post Office definition"><span class="ndv">Post Office</span></a>. In the 1930s, when he wrote some of his best poems, he was a leading member of a group of <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/left-wing_2" title="left-wing definition"><span class="ndv">left-wing</span></a> writers. Many of his most famous poems are in the collection <span class="ebi">Another Time</span> (1940). In 1946 he became a US citizen and his later poetry became more religious. His work has had a strong influence on later 20th-century poetry.</span></span>    <div id="ring-links-box">
